The proposed changes would need to be approved by the Town Council after a public hearing — most likely at the end of February – before they could go into effect. The town would also need to install signage before it could enforce the new policy. 

Residents have been concerned about parking on Shore Road for several years, especially in the summer, when tourists and visitors from greater Portland flock to Cliff House Beach. 

It’s known to locals as the “secret spot,” but has become an increasingly popular destination in the last five years. On beautiful sunny days, the beach sometimes sees more than a hundred sun-bathers. 

Neighbors have complained about the influx of parked cars on narrow residential roads. In 2021, the Town Council voted to ban parking on one side of Sea View Avenue and restrict parking on the other side to residents only. Parking on Glen Avenue also was restricted to residents only. 

[![](https://www.pressherald.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2024/07/38891750_20240702_cape_0003-1720093078.jpg?w=1024)](https://w2pcms.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/10/2024/07/38891750_20240702_cape_0003.jpg)

Cliff House Beach as viewed from the top of the stairs. (Ben McCanna/Staff Photographer)

This pushed beach visitors onto Shore Road, where they parked on wide shoulders on both sides of the street, creating another set of safety challenges. 

Tom Mikulka, who lives on Mountain View Road, said he can’t see the southbound side of the street when pulling onto Shore Road.

Advertisement

“You’re gambling,” he said. “You just have to hope there’s no one coming at 45 with a cell phone in their hand.” 

As complaints piled up, the Town Council two summers ago tasked the ordinance committee with tackling the parking issue. The committee considered eliminating parking on one side of Shore Road and restricting parking on residential streets. 

Police Chief Paul Fenton recommended that the town conduct a traffic and parking study to determine what changes would be needed if parking was banned on Shore Road.

The $37,000 price tag proved to be too steep for the council, and the study’s recommendations were ultimately not approved. 

Instead, in an effort to improve sight-lines from driveways, intersections and crosswalks, the public works department painted lines and boxes on the road last summer to visibly show the setbacks.

“We tried our best to address the safety concerns,” Fenton said.  

Advertisement

But some residents were not happy with the changes. Nearly 100 residents signed a petition that was presented to the council in July, urging the town to reverse the painted lines and reopen comment about road safety on Shore Road. 

A parking ban would mitigate some of these problems, according to some residents who live in the vicinity, at a town forum in September. In a parking survey sent to 250 residences, nearly half of the 98 respondents said there should be no parking at all on Shore Road near Cliff House Beach.

Fenton, who would ultimately oversee enforcement of parking changes, is wary of the potential unintended consequences. He’s worried that the parking would migrate to narrow, residential side streets that are ill-equipped for more cars.

“Parking is like water,” he said. “It doesn’t disappear. It just shows up somewhere else.”  

He said there have been talks about the possibility of hiring parking enforcement staff to enforce proposed regulations. The police department has only two officers working at any given time, Fenton said. 

The Town Council will likely vote to schedule a public hearing at its first February meeting. 

